node.text:
A small clip of my recent interview with Vishen on @MindValley talks. In this interview we cover:

~ Conscious Relationships and Relationship to Self
~ Emotional Healing through Partnership
~ Why We Push Love Away 
~ When to Stay and When to Go 
+ More questions from MindValley participants. 

Watch the Full talk here with @SheleanaAiyana of @RisingWoman on the @MindValley Youtube Channel: https://youtu.be/2J_wANhyqf4

node.title: This Interview Will Change The Way You Choose Your Partner

Join me for a discussion on the mature and conscious approach to outside attractions. @sheleanaaiyana

.

.

Lots of love, @createthelove and @sheleanaaiyana @risingwoman

node.text:
The Mother Daughter Relationship is complicated and for many of us, there's a lot to work out when it comes to how we relate to our past. I loved this conversation with @Harriet_Lerner and am really excited to share it with you today! 

Harriet is the author of many books including The Dance of Anger, and her latest is "Why Won't You Apologize?"

node.text:
What is underneath anxiety? Sadness, loss, grief… often what we find beneath the surface is a fear that if we surrender to the feeling underneath our anxiety we may be swallowed by the oceanic force of our pain and never find our way back.

But pain is a passage not a prison. It’s safe to surrender and allow yourself to go deep within. Often when we are overcome with anxiety it’s because we are resisting our reality - maybe we know we need to let go but we wish it weren’t so… perhaps everything is changing and we don’t want to accept it… breathe, return to your heartbeat, return to your body.

🌊 Oceanic Visualization + Somatic Practice for Anxiety 🌊

Place a hand on your heart and belly, feel the rise and fall of your breath.

Notice the sensations arising in your body - in your chest, legs, arms, face. Name them - tingle, tight, cool, warm etc.

Now return to your breath - is it heavy or shallow, simply notice.

Now go to the anxious energy in your body - where is it located? Does it have a shape, color? If the anxiety had words for you - what would it say?

Listen quietly, don’t overthink or script - simply allow your anxiety to do it’s job and serve as a messenger.

When you receive the message, perhaps you already know what emotion is present - you can also inquire and ask “what’s the feeling underneath this anxious feeling”?

Perhaps it’s sadness, fear, abandonment, loss… let it be for a moment and stay with your body.

There’s no need to run or shut down this feeling, you are safe to go deeper.

Visualize gentle ocean water washing over you, with each wave, imagine your body being held and cleansed.

With each wave washing over you, imagine that you are giving your sadness to the waters and letting them heal you.

With hands on your heart, thank your body for carrying you, your heart for beating, your breath for giving you life.

Slowly return to the space you are in, feel your feet or back planted on the earth, look around at your surroundings and say “my body is a safe place” “all of my emotions and sensations are welcome”.

Sending you so much love 💕 

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.text:
Creating safety is at the root of our ability to heal.

We cannot heal if we are in a triggered stage and we cannot heal if we are in an environment that’s rife with judgment, criticism and volatility.

While honesty and truth are vital to any healthy relationship, without gentleness and compassion our “truth” is nothing more than a product of our own ego.

All of our wounding from relationship occurs as a result of being left to tend to our pain alone - without connection, compassion or understanding.

We learn to wall off, hide, defend, numb or mask up - but ultimately underneath it all there is fear and a nervous system that’s stuck in a pattern as if the original injury is still happening.

This is why creating safety is the priority when it comes to our healing work. Our bodies need to be safe in order for pain to move through and out, and we need to co-regulate with other healthy and securely attached nervous systems to transform.

Individualistic healing work and teachings are on the mark when it comes to recognizing that we must heal ourselves to heal the world, but it cannot be done without the healing power of relationship - friendship, community, romantic - all are flavours of connection that have the power to wound us and to heal us.

Learning to listen, to empathize, to validate another’s reality, and to genuinely care for each other becomes easier when we are not deprived of this ourselves.

Questions about safety?

🌿@sheleanaaiyana

It shows the pain point running under the surface of our lives (core wound) and yet it also shows our greatest opportunity for growth in this lifetime. It represents our deepest gift to others and the world.

Once we discover how to unlock it and alchemize it, it becomes the key to our highest potential. No one is exempt from the challenge of Chiron, or the gifts once unlocked.

You can look up your Chiron at cafeastrology.com 
Check the house first and the sign second. Scroll through the slides to read about your Chiron house and sign🖤  + If you want to learn more about how to read charts for yourself and other’s - the doors for our new Become Your Own Astrologer Course are officially open. More on our website or in bio link.  Andrea is not only one of my dearest friends, she’s the COO of Rising Woman AND writes our astrology reports. She’s been doing readings for me for years and I have deep admiration for the way she layers multiple methods together to create an extremely accurate reading.

We also made sure to weave in trauma informed teachings into this program so that you can learn how to be extra mindful and nuanced with how you read a chart for someone else, as this is a very sacred responsibility!

node.text:
Hello friends 🌿

It’s been a while since I’ve introduced myself. My name is Sheleana (pronounced Shell-eee-nah) & you can call me Shay.

I am a woman of Slavic, Celtic and Indigenous Ancestry and I live and work on the unceded traditional territory of the Hul’qumi’num and SENĆOŦEN speaking peoples.

One of my love languages is food - I love to cook and nourish people, it brings me so much joy!

My childhood was my first container for spiritual learning - I grew up without a father, a mother battling deep trauma and mental illness, in and out of foster homes, and eventually working 2 jobs and living on my own at age 16.

Being highly sensitive meant I had to learn to self-protect. My survival instinct was to mask my vulnerability.   Over a decade, I've explored the deeper layers of my inner healing through every avenue that called me. For 6 years I have been sitting with Ayahuasca, though it is not something I often speak about and I don’t recommend it as it’s not my place to do so.  Plant-medicines are sacred and I believe we each must listen and wait until the plants call on us to work with them.

I’m passionate about healing our relationship patterns and making space for authentic love and connection because relationship is the fabric of our being. It’s why we are here. I’m not only referring to romantic love - but relationship as a whole - to the earth, to nature within and without, to our communities, to the plants and animals and the sky above.

Letting ourselves be seen and held by others is healing. Lacking in self-awareness can drive us to consume, compete and destroy. Having self-awareness can support us in living from the energy of reciprocity with everything and everyone around us.

I’m don’t call myself an influencer, a spiritual guru or an expert. I’m a guide & I take great care in this work I am so privileged to do.

My favourite way to connect with my audience is through group calls & I've got a workshop + Q&A call on Zoom coming up July 17th.

Find the registration link in my stories. Every single time, I'm moved to tears at the vulnerability, depth and warmth we co-create.

🌸 @SheleanaAiyana

👗Outfit is @maurieandeve - love their pieces!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Rising Woman on July 04, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Transforming our relationship patterns requires that we take ownership for our inner saboteur and deepen in self- awareness. It's not fun or easy to look at how we perpetuate our own relationship struggles, but the alternative is to claim a powerlessness over our lives. Taking ownership means that you have the power to change your story and get the love and connection your heart desires most.'.

node.text:
One of the main arguments that comes back whenever I write about ownership and self-awareness is that it somehow implies that we are responsible for finding ourselves in abusive or unsafe relationships - or that taking ownership means that we are responsible for how the other person shows up too.

None of this is in alignment with true ownership work or the practice of deepening in self-awareness to transform our own patterns.

I have been in trauma-bond relationships, I endured an incredibly violent relationship that left me with permanent physical damage - so please trust that I speak from experience but also many years of training.

We aren’t responsible for how others behave or show up, and, we can still explore how we show up, communicate, relate so that we can grow. This work is about internal freedom and a life that reflects our consciousness.

Taking ownership over our inner saboteur and being willing to acknowledge the ways we contribute to our own relationship struggles is vital - it is freeing - it is the ultimate seat of empowerment.

If we have nothing to do with our patterns that leaves us without any ability to change our story. So while looking inward and taking accountability is initially confronting and painful - it also means that we hold the power to change, to transform, to create something new.

The unconscious collective story is “there’s something wrong with the people I date but these experiences have nothing to do with me”. Sadly, this script while comforting - is also what enables us to stay stuck.

When we look within and own that we may at times:
.
Show up in ways that hurt others
Push love away
Be unkind, combative, dismissive, judgmental, defensive and so on, then we can finally catch ourselves in moments of stress and instead of responding from a conditioned place - try something new.

We can lower our shields and show our hearts - and that is what creates real change. The domino effect of being authentic and self-aware is choosing to surround ourselves with others who operate on the same frequency.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Rising Woman on July 03, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of text that says 'Most of the time, relationships die because we're withholding something- our truth, our energy, our desires. These are what we need to bring to the table if we want to experience aliveness together. Returning to an awakened state in partnership is possible if you're both willing and truly want it. If the willingness isn't there, it's ok to let go.'.

node.text:
Being awake together in partnership requires having the courage to speak it out loud when something hurts, when our mind is running wild on us, when we’re demonizing our beloved as an attempt to distance ourselves from the discomfort that arises more strongly than ever when in the romantic love.

In an awakened partnership there is no room for withholding, secret-keeping, stuffing or denying.

But not all relationships are meant to go to this level - and this is something we can learn to accept rather than trying to climb a mountain that’s built on sand.

Some relationships have to end in order for each person to grow in their own direction and find their path - and this is why if we see each partner as our spiritual teacher there can be a mutual gratitude for the lessons we learn together rather than stamping ourselves as failures just because this one didn’t last forever.

Together forever doesn’t have to be the goal, there is value in each connection we form so long as we bring an open-mind, curiosity, and compassion with us along the way.

Sometimes we are preparing each other for the next leg of the journey - and that's beautiful too. 

If one or both of you doesn’t have a deep well of willingness and desire to transform the energy and breathe new life into the partnership - then it’s time to let go. 

Have you stopped clearing resentments? Do you both share a mutual willingness and desire to experience aliveness and be awake together? Can you bring all of yourself to this relationships - and more than that, do you truly want to?
.
These are the questions to get honest about with one another.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Rising Woman on July 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'I don't want the honeymoon phase forever. I want the depth that can only come from having climbed tall mountains and walked the low valleys together. I don't want the butterflies of excitement and lust I want the peace of knowing a true and medicinal kind of love. One where we heal our past and make way for a better future because of who we inspire each other to be.'.

node.text:
When I was a younger woman, relationships were nothing more than a facet of consumption to me. I craved and crafted the honeymoon phase - the rushes of dopamine, the butterflies, thinking and fantasizing of The One - whoever they happened to be at this juncture.

When the honeymoon phase would end I’d be left with a hollow feeling in my belly along with confusion as to why is was ending. What’s wrong with me, I thought, why can’t I make this feeling last?

Only to realize that what I was experiencing was an old wound from childhood that had me addicted to the false sense of being someone’s entire world - it was my inner-child that needed the intensity of being chosen.

So much of our culture is enveloped in the false narrative that “true love” must feel like tsunami of feels forever, and so we often confuse the transition from new love to mature love for being broken.

The Honeymoon phase in many ways can be a bit of a selfish time - and it’s a beautiful phase.

One where you carve out extra time for this new person and the enamour is high. For a time, the focus is on exploration and discovery - it’s all very fresh and exciting!

But mature love doesn’t mean that you’ll no longer feel attracted to your partner or have moments of intensity or deep passion - it means that when you have those experiences, they’re more rooted.

Mature love is medicinal - it has had time to work in you both and alchemize the unique ingredients you’ve each brought to the partnership.

I don't want the honeymoon phase forever. I want the depth that can only come from having climbed tall mountains and walked the low valleys together.

I don't want the butterflies of excitement and lust, I want the peace of knowing a true and medicinal kind of love.

One where we heal our past and make way for a better future because of who we inspire each other to be.

The kind of love that is calm and devoted, playful and energizing.

The kind of love that does not consume all of the energy between us like a vacuum but serves as a power grid to redistribute our gifts throughout our community and world - a love that gives us the energy to serve higher.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Rising Woman on June 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'A relationship is like an orchard. When you plant an apple seed, you must tend to it, water it and nourish it for years before it produces fruit. We don't expect seeds to grow into apple trees without our time, energy and commitment, so why do we expect this from our relationships? Tend to your relationship as though it is a precious seed and watch it bloom for you.'.

node.text:
Relationships really do take time to evolve and grow. Just like an apple seed, they need time, water and love before they produce the fruit we are hungry for.

We live in a time where relationships are idealized and the messaging to never settle and find your “conscious partner” is amplified; and this is a beautiful thing!

We also need to make sure we don’t get caught in the hidden trap in this messaging - thinking that if the relationship isn’t everything we want it to be right now, we should move on and find someone better.

If you both share mutual love, safety, trust and willingness to put in the work, know that growing a relationship into its highest expression can take years, a decade even.

And of course, it’s important that we choose to put in this time and energy with a willing partner who actually wants to grow.

Nourish the seed of your relationship and watch it bloom for you.

🌿🍎@sheleanaaiyana

node.text:
This place is not new
But it never gets old
These trees never move
but each time I come
they move me, in one way
or another

These trees do not speak aloud,
But if they had words 
they would tell me I am safe here
they have seen broken spirits and sad hearts pass through them quietly
seeking solace and refuge

They have watched lovers pass through
hand in hand
heads in the clouds
bodies thirsty

they have watched lonely souls 
walk slowly, looking up to the sky
with a wanting in their eyes

oh what they have seen 
for generations, standing tall
giving shade, never to move, only to sway and gently bend,
the roots run deep, they’ve seen it all

they have watched children run wildly, mothers trailing behind
they have watched the same people 
day by day, passing through
same trail, different story, new memories

they have watched hearts come in broken
leaving renewed
they have seen thousands of winters, thousands of springs
they have been birthing grounds, and a place of death and dying
over and over, their cycles repeat

this place is not new
but it is never the same
the trees do not speak aloud
but if they had words
they would tell me I am doing just fine
that in some ways, we are the same
transforming over, and over, and over
again.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana - Written in 2015 as I emerged from a deep cocoon of grief. My rituals were days wandering the forest, cold river dips, spring water runs and laying on the earth. The trees, plants, flowers and waters held me through it. I met my husband 3 months after this I wrote this passage.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Rising Woman on June 25, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of text that says 'If we do not listen, we cannot learn. If we do not grieve, we cannot heal. Let us do the work we're here to do, so we may pass down love instead of pain.'.

node.text:
We are here now for a reason. Let us practice listening and softening. Without the willingness to be curious and open, we cannot learn. Without the courage to grieve, we cannot heal.

Our ancestors pain and trauma lives through us until we have the humility, the trust, the softness to look inward and break the cycle.

It is in holding our own grief as sacred that we may have the capacity to hold others in theirs.

It is in healing our own past that we may have the inner resources to see the beauty in all beings and extend kindness and compassion outward.

If we have ignored our own wounds and become bitter - we will resent anyone who asks us to listen, to care, to slow down. Why should we care about their pain, no one cared about ours? That is the poison that runs through our societies.

Each of us needs to care now more than ever - to slow down and listen inward, to heal ourselves so that we can pass down love instead of pain and break the cycles that are begging for change.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana
